Facial Emotion Detection¶

Problem Definition¶

The context: Why is this problem important to solve?

In the field of human-machine interaction, facial expression recognition is critical. From recent research, it has been found that as much as 55% of communication of sentiment takes place through facial expressions and other visual cues. Therefore, training a model to identify facial emotions accurately is an important step towards the development of emotionally intelligent behavior in machines with AI capabilities. Automatic facial expression recognition systems could have many applications, including but not limited to any use case that requires human behavior understanding, detection of mental disorders, and creating a higher quality of virtual assistant for customer-facing businesses.

The objectives: What is the intended goal?

The goal of this project is to use Deep Learning and Artificial Intelligence techniques to create a computer vision model that can accurately detect facial emotions.

The key questions: What are the key questions that need to be answered?

  • Is our data balanced? Are there enough samples and are the samples evenly distributed among our classes?
  • What colorspace (rgb vs grayscale) will produce better results? My hypothesis is that feeding rgb images into our models will generate better results at the cost of higher computation times.
  • How impactful will transfer learning be when compared to our base CNN models?



The problem formulation: What are we trying to solve using data science?

We are building a model that will be able to perform multi-class classification on images of facial expressions, to classify the expressions according to the associated emotion.

About the dataset¶

The data set consists of 3 folders, i.e., 'test', 'train', and 'validation'. Each of these folders has four subfolders:

‘happy’: Images of people who have happy facial expressions.
‘sad’: Images of people with sad or upset facial expressions.
‘surprise’: Images of people who have shocked or surprised facial expressions.
‘neutral’: Images of people showing no prominent emotion in their facial expression at all.

Observations and Insights:

The unique features that stand out from the "Happy" images are:

  • the smile (teeth showing in many of them / the shape of their mouth)
  • raised eyebrows
  • raised cheeks

#loading training data labels
training_labels = []

def create_training_labels():
  for category in CATEGORIES:
    path = os.path.join(DATADIR, category)
    class_num = category

    for img in os.listdir(path): #iterating through every file in directory
      training_labels.append(class_num) #appending image array and class label

Observations and Insights:

  • Training data: The classes Happy, Neutral, and Sad have about the same distribution each having 26% (approx 4000 samples) of the data, whereas the class Surprise only has 21% (approx 3200 samples) of the data.
  • Test data: The distribution of the classes are the same.
  • Validation data: The distribution of the classes are as follows: happy (36%), neutral (24%), sad (23%), and surprise (16%).

I don't believe at this moment that the imbalance in our training data is too high, but the imbalance of classes in our validation data may cause performance issues in our models.

Model Building¶

CNNs vs ANNS CNNs have two main advantages over ANNs when working on image data:

  1. Local Spatiality
    • ANNs do a poor job at understanding local representation/patterns in the image data because ANNs needs images to be flattened into a 1D vector. This means that the vector of a flattened image and the vector of that same image but slightly rotated by x degrees produce vastly different vectors for our ANN.
  2. Weight Sharing
    • In CNNs we use filters to detect features from an image, and the weights of any filter remain the same for all the patches in an image. Therefore information is extracted from the entire image instead of just a particular region.
    • Whereas ANNs don't have any weight sharing, each input node is multiplied by a weight of its own.

For the reasons above, we will be using CNNs to build our models.

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In [56]:
batch_size  = 32

datagen_train = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip = True,
                                    brightness_range=(0.,2.),
                                    rescale=1./255,
                                    shear_range=0.2,)

train_set = datagen_train.flow_from_directory(DATADIR,
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = 'grayscale' ,
                                              batch_size = batch_size,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)


datagen_val = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip = True,
                                    brightness_range=(0.,2.),
                                    rescale=1./255,
                                    shear_range=0.2,)

val_set = datagen_val.flow_from_directory(DATADIR_VAL,
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = 'grayscale' ,
                                              batch_size = batch_size,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)


datagen_test = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip = True,
                                    brightness_range=(0.,2.),
                                    rescale=1./255,
                                    shear_range=0.2,)

test_set = datagen_test.flow_from_directory(DATADIR_TEST,
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = 'grayscale' ,
                                              batch_size = batch_size_testing,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

def cnn_model_base():

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1))) #, input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    
    model.add(Flatten())

    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model

Observations and Insights:¶
  • The model clearly overfits our training data: our validation data accuracy (68%) and loss (0.8) start to plateau at the around the 14th epoch while our training data continues to improve, slowing down at around the 23rd epoch.
  • It is therefore not giving a generalized performance.
  • Our learning rate of 0.01 seems to have worked pretty well on our training data, achieving 77% accuracy at the 24th epoch.
  • The accuracy on the test set is just under 68% which is similar to the accuracy of our validation data.

Second Base CNN (grayscale)¶

Let's try a smaller SGD learning rate in our base cnn model (lr = 0.001) to compare.

Defining and Compiling the Model¶

In [74]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [75]:
def cnn_model_base1():

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1))) #, input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    
    model.add(Flatten())

    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.001, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [76]:
cnn_base1 = cnn_model_base1()
cnn_base1.summary()

Observations and Insights: TODO¶
  • The model is still overfitting the training data. This makes sense as we did not add any dropout layers to reduce overfitting and that this model is identical to the previous with the only change being the learning rate.
  • The higher learning rate performed better on the test set and was much quicker to achieve better results than the lower learning rate. However, we can say that the lower learning rate gave us a slightly better generalized performance (training and validation sets accuracy are slightly closer to one another).
  • We should try different learning rates between the two. We'll do more hyperparameter tuning at the end. For the sake of simplicity, lets go with a learning rate of 0.01 for the SGD optimizer for the rest of our models and compare. We will tune this hyperparameter later on when we try to find our best model for this problem.
  • The accuracy on the training set is much lower than our previous base model, sitting at 66% versus 77%. Which indicates that the learning rate might be too low and our model is not learning quick enough (this model ran for almost double the epochs of our previous one and performed worse on all three sets of data).

Third CNN (grayscale)¶

Let's try a slightly larger architecture

Defining and Compiling the Model¶

In [86]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [87]:
def cnn_model_1(): 

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1))) #input layer

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) # conv1
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 2
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))


    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 3
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 4
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Flatten())

    model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(Dense(128, activation = 'relu'))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')) #output layer

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [88]:
cnn_1 = cnn_model_1()
cnn_1.summary()

Model: "sequential"

Observations and Insights:

  • Our best grayscale CNN yet when evaluated on the test set: 73% accuracy.
  • Our validation loss (0.76) starts to plateau at the 17th epoch, while it continues to improve with respect to our training data.
  • The accuracy on our training data reached 80% and on our validation data 72% at the 22nd epoch.
  • We should consider adding dropout layers in future iterations to reduce the overfitting we've been seeing across our past 3 models.
  • This model is not giving a generalized performance even though it has performed better than our previous ones with respect to the test set.
  • We will try more complex models down the line, and also see if we can optimize this one by changing the architecture to reduce overfitting, but for now lets use this model and the better base CNN model with rgb images to compare.

RGB¶

Using and comparing our base CNN and our third CNN grayscale models to accept rgb images and find out whether rgb image makes an impact on performance.

Reinitializing our DataLoaders to change color mode to rgb¶

In [98]:
batch_size  = 32

datagen_train = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip = True,
                                    brightness_range=(0.,2.),
                                    width_shift_range = 0.2,
                                    height_shift_range = 0.2,
                                    rescale=1./255,
                                    zoom_range = 0.2,
                                    shear_range=0.2,
                                    fill_mode = 'nearest')

train_set = datagen_train.flow_from_directory(DATADIR,
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = 'rgb' ,
                                              batch_size = batch_size,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

Base CNN Model (rgb)¶

Defining and Compiling the Model¶

backend.clear_session()
In [102]:

In [103]:
def cnn_model_base_rgb():

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3))) #, input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    
    model.add(Flatten())

    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [104]:
cnn_base_rgb = cnn_model_base_rgb()

Observations and Insights:

  • The many spikes in our validation data graphs could stem from the imbalance in the validation data that we saw earlier in preprocessing.
  • This rgb version of our base model did not perform nearly as well.
  • Our accuracy and loss for our training and validation sets plateaued at around 63% and 0.87 respectively.
  • However, we can say that this model gives generalized performance because of how close the performance of training and validation are to one another. This is interesting since our grayscale version did not, and we did not change anything except for the colormode of our images.
  • This model achieved an accuracy of 64% on our test set, recall that the grayscale version acheived an accuracy of 68%.
  • For now, we can say that our grayscale models are better, but lets try one more.

Second CNN Model (rgb)¶

In [115]:
def cnn_model_rgb1(): 

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3))) #input layer

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) # conv1
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 2
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))


    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 3
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 4
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Flatten())

    model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(Dense(128, activation = 'relu'))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')) #output layer

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model

4/4 - 0s - 23ms/step - accuracy: 0.7656 - loss: 0.5794
In [121]:
#saving model name and accuracy
scoreboard_name.append('cnn1_rgb')
scoreboard_acc.append(accuracy)

scoreboard.append(['cnn1_rgb', accuracy[1]])

Observations and Insights:

  • We've achieved the highest accuracy on our test set so far: 76%
  • The accuracy and loss for our training and validation data have plateaued at around 71% and 0.68 respectively.
  • These numbers are lower than our comparative grayscale model but this model has performed better on the test set. A reason could be that this test set is not identical since we've generated a new test set when we changed the colormode in our Data Loader.
  • We can also still see the imbalance of our validation data reflected above by the spikes in the graph.
  • However, this model gives a generalized performance as it seems that the validation data "corrects" itself to match more closely with our training data.
  • At this point, it is hard to say if this model is better than our grayscale version even though it performed better on the test set because of the points above.
  • At this point, I'd suggest to stick to grayscale and finetune the hyperparameters. The rgb models take a much longer time to train, and has not made it clear that it gives a big performance boost compared to its grayscale counterparts.

Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we will create several Transfer Learning architectures. For the pre-trained models, we will select three popular architectures namely, VGG16, ResNet v2, and Efficient Net. The difference between these architectures and the previous architectures is that these will require 3 input channels while the earlier ones worked on 'grayscale' images.

NOTE

We don't need to create new Data Loaders for our transfer learning architectures since our current ones already have the color mode RGB.

VGG16 Model¶

Importing the VGG16 Architecture¶

In [128]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [129]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras import Model

vgg_model = VGG16(include_top = False, weights = 'imagenet', input_shape = (48, 48, 3))
vgg_model.summary()

Model Building¶

  • Import VGG16 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [131]:
transfer_layer = vgg_model.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg_model.trainable = False
In [132]:
x = Flatten()(transfer_layer.output)

x = Dense(256, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = Dense(128, activation = 'relu')(x)

x = Dropout(0.3)(x)

x = Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)

x = BatchNormalization()(x)

pred = Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')(x)

vgg_model_1 = Model(vgg_model.input, pred)

Compiling and Training the VGG16 Model¶

In [134]:
opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

vgg_model_1.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])
In [135]:
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 5, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_vgg_model.keras', monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', verbose = 1, save_best_only = True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = 'val_loss', factor = 0.2, patience = 3, verbose = 1, min_delta = 0.0001)

history_vgg = vgg_model_1.fit(train_set, validation_data = val_set, epochs = 200, verbose = 1, callbacks = [early_stop, checkpoint, reduce_lr])

Observations and Insights:

  • The accuracy of the training data continually improves up until the 12th epoch where it starts to oscillate.
  • Overall the training performance starts well and starts to plateau rather quickly.
  • The accuracy of the validation data starts oscillating to a much bigger degree as of the 3rd epoch.
  • Let's try another transfer learning architecture.

ResNet V2 Model¶

Model Building¶

  • Import VGG16 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [147]:
#importing until conv5_block3_add layer
transfer_layer_resnet = Resnet.get_layer('conv5_block3_add')
In [148]:
x = Flatten()(transfer_layer_resnet.output)

x = Dense(256, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = Dense(128, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)
x = Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)

x = BatchNormalization()(x)

pred = Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')(x)

resnetmodel = Model(Resnet.input, pred)

Compiling and Training the Model¶

In [150]:
opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

resnetmodel.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])
In [151]:
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 5, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_resnet_model.keras', monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', verbose = 1, save_best_only = True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = 'val_loss', factor = 0.2, patience = 3, verbose = 1, min_delta = 0.0001)

history_resnet = resnetmodel.fit(train_set, validation_data = val_set, epochs = 20, verbose = 1, callbacks = [early_stop, checkpoint, reduce_lr])

accuracy = resnetmodel.evaluate(test_images, test_labels, verbose = 2)

4/4 - 0s - 83ms/step - accuracy: 0.3359 - loss: 1.3995
In [155]:
#saving model name and accuracy
scoreboard_name.append('resnet')
scoreboard_acc.append(accuracy)

scoreboard.append(['resnet', accuracy[1]])

Observations and Insights:

  • Our early stopping has stopped the model at the first epoch because of no improvement at the 5th epoch.
  • Over the 5 epochs the training accuracy has been pretty much constant but the training loss slightly improved (1.44 to 1.39).
  • We could try lowering the learning rate to 0.001 and forcing the model to run for more epochs to see if we get better performance, but for now lets move on to our final transfer learning architecture.
In [ ]:
**Think About It:**

- What do you infer from the general trend in the training performance?
- Is the training accuracy consistently improving?
- Is the validation accuracy also improving similarly?

x = Flatten()(transfer_layer_efficientnet.output)

x = Dense(256, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = Dense(128, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)

x = BatchNormalization()(x)

pred = Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')(x)

en_model = Model(EfficientNet.input, pred)

Observations and Insights:

  • The model has not learned anything from our training set in 6 epochs -- the training set accuracy and loss have remained constant.
  • Efficient Net has performed the worse, although the bar has been low, out of our transfer learning architectures.

Final Transfer Learning Architectures Takeaways

  • The best performing model of the three transfer learning architectures was the VGG16 model, with an accuracy of 44% on the test set.
  • They performed very poorly compared to the models we built from scratch.
  • The differences in our datasets (train, val, and test) and those on which these models were trained/tested on may have cause the performance issues we are seeing. For example, the dimensions of our input images or domain mismatch.
  • Let's move away from transfer learning and back to grayscale.

Building a Complex Neural Network Architecture¶

In this section, we will build a more complex Convolutional Neural Network Model that has close to as many parameters as we had in our Transfer Learning Models. However, we will have only 1 input channel for our input images.

Creating our Data Loaders'.¶

                                    brightness_range=(0.,2.),
                                    rescale=1./255,
                                    shear_range=0.2,)

train_set = datagen_train.flow_from_directory(DATADIR,
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = 'grayscale' ,

                                              class_mode = 'categorical',

                                              shuffle = True)

                                    rescale=1./255,
                                    shear_range=0.2,)

val_set = datagen_val.flow_from_directory(DATADIR_VAL,

                                              batch_size = batch_size,

Fourth CNN Model (grayscale)¶

Model Building and Compiling¶

In [179]:
backend.clear_session()

In [180]:
def cnn_model_complex():
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    # conv1 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (2,2), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv2 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (2,2), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv3 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (2,2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv4 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (2,2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv5 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (2,2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    #flatten
    model.add(Flatten())

    #Dense layers
    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))

    model.add(Dense(512))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [181]:
cnn4 = cnn_model_complex()
cnn4.summary()

Training the Model¶

In [183]:
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 5, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_model_cnn4.keras', monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', verbose = 1, save_best_only = True)

history_cnn4 = cnn4.fit(train_set, validation_data = val_set, epochs = 200, verbose = 1, callbacks = [early_stop, checkpoint, reduce_lr])

Observations and Insights:

  • Our first more complex grayscale model has a train and validation accuracy of 66% and 70% by the 40th epoch, and a test accuracy of 68%.
  • This is below our simpler architecture (third grayscale CNN model).
  • However, we do no have overfitting here, if anything, the model is underfitting training data.
  • The difference with our third CNN is that we chose a kernel size of 2x2 for our convolutional layers, let's change that in the next iteration.

Fifth CNN Model (grayscale)¶

Model Building and Compiling¶

Changes

  • Lets set the kernel size in our convulutional layers to 3x3
In [193]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [194]:
def cnn_model_complex1():
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    # conv1 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv2 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv3 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv4 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv5 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    #flatten
    model.add(Flatten())

    #Dense layers
    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))

    model.add(Dense(512))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [195]:
cnn5 = cnn_model_complex1()

Observations and Insights:

  • The increase in kernel size seems to have benefitted our model.
  • This model is also giving a generalized performance.
  • We are now sitting at an accuracy of about 71% for both of our training and validation data (an increase of 5% and 1% respectively).
  • The accuracy on our test is has also increased by 4% from 68% to 72%.
  • Let's stick with this kernel size and lower our learning rate and see if it has a similar effect as what happened with our base CNN models where the higher training rate performed better than the lower one.

Sixth CNN Model (grayscale)¶

Changes

  • Let's change our SGD learning rate from 0.01 to 0.001 and compare, earlier we saw that the higher learning rate produced better results more quickly.

Model Building and Compiling¶

In [207]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [208]:
def cnn_model_complex2():
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    # conv1 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv2 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv3 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv4 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # conv5 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    #flatten
    model.add(Flatten())

    #Dense layers
    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))

    model.add(Dense(512))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.001, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [209]:
cnn6 = cnn_model_complex2()
cnn6.summary()

Model: "sequential"

Training the Model¶

In [211]:
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 5, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_model_cnn6.keras', monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', verbose = 1, save_best_only = True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = 'val_loss', factor = 0.2, patience = 3, verbose = 1, min_delta = 0.0001)

history_cnn6 = cnn6.fit(train_set, validation_data = val_set, epochs = 200, verbose = 1, callbacks = [early_stop, checkpoint, reduce_lr])

Observations and Insights:

  • It seems like again, the lower initial training rate negatively impacted our models training and validation accuracies.
  • However, this model has produced better results on the test set. The accuracy has improved by 2% and the loss has stayed about the same.
  • We also note that our validation data has performed better than our training data which could be due to the imbalances that we have.
  • We have also lost a bit of the generalized performance that we got with our previous model with the higher learning rate.

Seventh CNN Model (grayscale)¶

Model Building and Compiling¶

Changes

  • Let's change the number of filters in our first and third convolutional block (fewer filters)
  • Let's also choose a learning rate between our last two attempts and set it to 0.005
  • Removing some dropout layers and increase the ones with have to 0.3 instead of 0.2
In [221]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [222]:
def cnn_model_complex3():
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

    # conv1 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))

    # conv2 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    # conv3 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))

    # conv4 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    # conv5 block
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 512, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2)))

    #flatten
    model.add(Flatten())

    #Dense layers
    model.add(Dense(256))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    model.add(Dense(512))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.005, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [223]:
cnn7 = cnn_model_complex3()
cnn7.summary()

Training the Model¶

In [225]:
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 5, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_model_cnn7.keras', monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', verbose = 1, save_best_only = True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = 'val_loss', factor = 0.2, patience = 3, verbose = 1, min_delta = 0.0001)

history_cnn7 = cnn7.fit(train_set, validation_data = val_set, epochs = 200, verbose = 1, callbacks = [early_stop, checkpoint, reduce_lr])

Observations and Insights:

  • Our current best model performance on the test set sitting at about 83% accuracy and 0.55 loss, an increase of 9% accuracy and decrease of 0.05 loss compared to our last model.
  • This model is giving a generalized performance, this looks very promising.
  • The accuracy and loss of our training and validation data sits around 72% and 0.68 respectively, an increase of 4% accuracy compared to our last model (loss is similar).
  • It looks like we are getting to a sweet spot with respect to learning rate, dropout layers, and the number of filters.

Eighth CNN Model (grayscale) Improving Third CNN Model¶

Model Building and Compiling¶

  • Let's go back to our third cnn from earlier and see if we can optimize its performance by adding a few dropout layers
In [277]:
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(25)
random.seed(25)
tf.random.set_seed(25)
In [278]:
def cnn_model_1v2(): 

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Input(shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1))) #input layer

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) # conv1
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 2
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))


    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 3
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation = 'relu', padding='same')) #conv 4
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
    
    model.add(Flatten())

    model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    
    model.add(Dense(128, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    model.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')) #output layer

    opt = SGD(learning_rate = 0.01, momentum = 0.9)

    model.compile(loss = "categorical_crossentropy", optimizer = opt, metrics = ["accuracy"])

    return model
In [279]:

Training the Model¶

In [284]:
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', patience = 5, verbose = 1, restore_best_weights = True)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_model_cnn1v2.keras', monitor='val_loss', mode = 'min', verbose = 1, save_best_only = True)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor = 'val_loss', factor = 0.2, patience = 3, verbose = 1, min_delta = 0.0001)

history_cnn8 = cnn8.fit(train_set, validation_data = val_set, epochs = 200, verbose = 1, callbacks = [early_stop, checkpoint, reduce_lr])

Observations and Insights: TODO

  • model is giving a slightly worse generalized performance than our previous one but a better generalized performance with respect to its counterpart (Third CNN).
  • We've successfully increased its performance from its previous iteration (Third CNN)
  • We got an accuracy of 78% on the test set and an accuracy of 73% and 72% on the training and validation data respectively by the 35th epoch with no improvement afterward.

Observations and Insights:

  1. Classification Report
    • We have an overall accuracy of 83%, with the highest accuracy and recall belonging to class 3 (surprise) of 94% and 97% respectively.
    • The class 0 has done almost just as well with an accuracy and recall of 91% and 94% respectively.
    • The class 1 and 2 have not done as well in comparison.
    • Class 1 has an accuracy of 78% and a recall of 74% which is quite a bit lower.
    • Class 2 performed the worse with an accuracy and recall of 69%.
    • The support shows us that the model predicted class 1 the most, followed by class 2, and then equally classes 0 and 3.



  1. Confusion Matrix
    • The confusion matrix reinforces our findings from our classification report.
    • It also shows us something interesting to note: class 1 and 2 are most often confused with one another by our chosen model.
    • For class 1 (sad): 7 of the 32 samples are wrongly predicted as neutral but not any of the other two classes.
    • For class 2 (neutral): 7 of the 32 samples are wrongly predicted as sad, 2 as happy, and 1 as surprise.
    • If we jump back to our visualization of each of our classes, we can see that some features of the images were shared between the sad and neutral classes (i.e. the shape of the mouth) whereas our happy and surprise classes had more "unique" features.

Conclusion¶

Refined Insights:¶

  • CNN models were chosen for this problem as they carry two main advantages over their ANN counterpart discussed earlier: Local Spatiality and Weight Sharing.
  • We saw that the distribution of classes within our testing data and validation data weren't evenly distributed. Our testing data had 5% fewer samples of the "surprise" class. Whereas, our validation's data distribution was as follows: happy (36%), neutral (24%), sad (23%), and surprise (16%).
  • The classes happy and surprise seemed to have the most "unique" features whereas the classes "sad" and "neutral" seemed to be the most similar just based on looking at our images.
  • Of the two colorscales tested, grayscale ultimately produced the best result, although there is room for more testing here as we did not try our final chosen model with the rgb colormode for a more accurate representation.
  • The transfer learning models failed in helping us achieve better performance.
  • We end up settling on a complex and self-built architecture model as it performed most optimally on our testing data.

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

  • The are some clear winners and losers when it comes to the performance of our models. Our transfer models in general did not perform as well as our custom built models on the test data. We saw that our Third CNN model beat all others (even the Seventh) in terms of accuracy on our testing data (78%) but it did not perform as well on the validation data (72%).
  • Note that we mentioned earlier a couple reasons why the transfer learning models may not have performed as well as one might expect. Those were: domain mismatch and the difference between our input images and those that the pretrained model were trained on.
  • There is definitely scope for improvement. I would go back to our Third and Seventh CNNs and continue to tune different hyperparameters (ex: find the optimal learning rate, number and value of dropout layers, etc) to increase their performance. We settled on a model giving 83% accuracy on the test set, but I do believe this number could be brought higher also in terms of how well it does on the training and validations sets.
  • Another area that may lead to improvement would be to try different optimizers. In this solution we stuck to Stochastic Gradient Descent, but in future research trying out a different optimizer like Adam may yield better results.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

I propose adopting our Seventh CNN model as it clearly beat all other models on new data (the test set). It also gave a generalized performance which is what we are looking for in a good model. A reason it beat out other models was because of hyperparameter tuning: over several iterations we changed the number of filters in convolutional blocks, tested different SGD learning rates, and also played around with dropout layers which ultimately led to its success.
